    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-08-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-08-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="54"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d54">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.AC/8–146</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Carl M. Marcy, of the Division
                        of International Organization Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-08-01">August 1,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#top #nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>Mr. Fahy–<gloss target="#t_Le1">Le</gloss>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Miss Whiteman–<gloss target="#t_Le1">Le</gloss>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Halderman–<gloss target="#t_OA1">OA</gloss>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Marcy—<gloss target="#t_OA1">OA</gloss>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>At Mr. Fahy’s request, the meeting was held in his office to discuss steps which
                    the Department of State should take in connection with the Convention on
                    Privileges and Immunities of the United Nations.</p>
                <p>After some discussion, there was agreement that it would be proper to submit the
                    Convention to Congress for its approval by a joint <pb facs="0113" n="95"
                        xml:id="pg_95"/> resolution. There was also agreement that the Department of
                    State should submit the Convention to the Bureau of the Budget for clearance
                    prior to submitting it to the Congress. It was agreed that <gloss
                        target="#t_OA1">OA</gloss> would, in consultation with <gloss
                        target="#t_Le1">Le</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_RP1">RP</gloss>, prepare
                    the necessary communications.</p>
            </div>
